Fried", "Alice Let's Eat"

00:00:15.920 --> 00:00:19.940
and "Third Helping" the
so-called tummy trilogy recount

00:00:19.940 --> 00:00:23.410
in wonderful detail meals
he has eaten both the good

00:00:23.410 --> 00:00:26.690
and less frequently the bad.

00:00:26.690 --> 00:00:30.880
In our family, we still
quote one of his essays

00:00:30.880 --> 00:00:35.580
in which he quoted a daughter
dismissing inferior bagels

00:00:35.580 --> 00:00:37.900
as round bread.

00:00:37.900 --> 00:00:39.200
That's not a bagel.

00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:41.970
That's just round bread.

00:00:41.970 --> 00:00:47.420
Calvin Trillin is the
[inaudible] of pleasure, I think,

00:00:47.420 --> 00:00:51.340
not in any fussy overly
aesthetic way

00:00:51.340 --> 00:00:54.910
but in the honest pleasure
that's to be found in a stack

00:00:54.910 --> 00:01:02.250
of barbecued ribs or a decent
honest bagel or fresh corn,

00:01:02.250 --> 00:01:06.200
or as in his novel,
"Temper Isn't Going Out.

00:01:06.200 --> 00:01:09.480
The Pleasure of the
Perfect Parking Spot."

00:01:09.480 --> 00:01:15.330
I love what Wikipedia had to say
about Temper Isn't Going Out.

00:01:15.330 --> 00:01:19.000
It said, " It is unusual
among novels

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:22.690
